gard the longer-term\nfuture with assurance.\u201d\nThe trust company foresaw:\n1. Need for adoption of a long-range\nplan of relief expenditures at times\nof economic stress, as contrasted with\nthe \u201cspasmodic, wasteful and poorly\nplanned disbursements\u201d of the past.\n2. Need for some definite plan for\nbalancing the budget, such as broad\nening the tax base and reducing ex\npenditures.\n3. Need for a systematic program\nfor reducing the huge public debt\n(when a balanced budget is achieved\nand conditions warrant).\nIn respect to labor, it said there is\n\u201can urgent necessity for some ap\nproach to industrial problems that will\nenable the Government, business men\nand labor to consider their differences\nin a spirit of co-operation.\u201d\nRegarding the 1938 busineas out\nlook. the trust company said:\n\"While most competent observers\nanticipate that recession will continue\nwell into the coming year, many be\nlieve that there is nothing of a purely\neconomic nature apparent at present\nto suggest that we are entering a de\npression of the magnitude and dura\ntion of the last one.\u201d\nWashington Produce\nBUTTER\u201492 score. 1-pound prints\n4tubs. 41 \u20194-pound prints. 43; 90 score\ni-pound prints. 40; tubs. 39. '4-pound\nprints. 41.\nMEATS\u2014Choice, beef. 23: calves. 18:\nlambs 21: veal J9 sows. 15: fresh pork\n19 frozen pork. 20: pork loin 30: fresh\nnam. 19: large skinned ham 18 smoked\nham. 26: smoked skinned ham. 23: sliced\nbacon. 35: piece bacon. 30; compound.\nJ312. lard 12\nLIVE 8TOCK Pigs T^aT\u2019a: light pias.\nva734: medium. 734a8 230-250 pounds\n7 \u2019^a7*4: heavies. 7; sows. 6'aa8. stags.\n4a5 calves, l 1 'aal2.\nPrices paid shippers *net fob Wash\nington* by the U. 8. Bureau of Agricul\ntural Economics:\nEOG8 -Market steady at unchanged\nprices. Government graded and dated\neggs: White U. 8. extras, large. 33; U. 8.\nextras, mediums. 29: U. S standards,\nlarge. 31 U S. standards, mediums. 26.\nNearbv ungraded eggs: Curr