 ON\nIMPROVED\nPROPERTY\nin the\nDistrict of Columbia\nNearby Maryland\nand Virginia\nAlto\nMonthly Payment\nLoant\nPrompt Action\nB. F. SAUL CO.\n925 15th Street Natl. 2100\nDowntrend Starting in April\nCuts Housing Increase\nto 8 Per Cent.\nSpecial Dispatch to Tho Star.\nNEW YORK, Dec. 27.\u2014Starting In\n1928, the contraction in annual build\ning permit values grew tighter each\nyear until 1933, when the total was\n90 8 per cent smaller than that for\n1927, according to a survey by Dun\nBradstreet, Inc.\nWhile the slow advance in 1934\nwas quickened in 1935, it was not until\n1936 that an expansion in building\nwork started, following its precipitous\nfive-year slide. The 1936 volume was\ntriple that of 1933, double that of\n1934, and 64.3 per cent larger than\nthe 1935 aggregate. For the first\nquarter of 1937, the fourth year of the\nuptrend, the rise was extended by 49 2\nper cent from the 1936 period.\n\"In April a downtrend started,\nwhich by June had carried the com\npilation under the previous year's\ncomparative for the first time in two\nand one-half years. This cut the\n1937 six-month gain over 1936 to\n26.4 per cent. By the end of No\nvember, the increase in building per\nmit values over the 1936 eleven\nmonths had been reduced to 12.8 per\ncent. The number of dwelling units\nconstructed during the first 10 months\nof 1937 was reported by the Depart\nment of Labor as only 8 per cent more\nthan in the 1936 period, as against\n40 per cent in the six-month compar\nison.\n\"Vacancy decreases, in the mean\ntime, spread from around 8 per cent\nof the total number of dwelling units\nat the end of 1932, vacancies In many\nlarge cities were cut to as low as 3\nSTOP PAYING RENT\nBuy Your Own Homo\nPay the same per month as you\nnow pay in rent\u2014own your home\noutright in less than 20 years.\nMay wa halp?\n[Shannon&luchS\nMarUar* l.oan Corre'pondtnla\nINVESTORS SYNDICATE\n1505 H St. N.W. Natl. 2345\nand 1 per rent this year. Tht resi\ndential rent Index dropped in No\nvember. after an unbroken monthly\nrise since January. 193*. At mid-\nDecember, prices of building materials\nwere down about 4 per cent from the\nyear s high in May.\nFactory building, which revived\nhaltingly in 1933, had progressed suf\nficiently in 1936 to reach 42 per cent\nof the 1926 average, as computed by\nthe F. W. Dodge Corp. While this\npercentage would have been lifted bv\nthe innumerable plans approved for\n1937. it was found that new form* of\ntaxation would leave surplua inad\nequate to permit expansion programs.\nNew home building has been post\nponed. in order to receive the benefit\nof easier financing methods proposed\nby the Government. As a result, No\nvember building permit values sang\nto a 21 month low,\n\u201cAt *69,567,549. the November total\nof building permit values, for the 215\ncities reporting regularly to Dun\nBradstrgpt. Inc., was 7 9 per cent be\nlow last year's at $75,506,623. It was\nthe fifth month in 1937 to drop from\nthe corresponding one in 1936.\u201d\nRUBBER FUTURES.\nNEW YORK. Dec. 27 if..-Crude njW\nbrr futures opened 2 lower to 5 hither.\n.March 15.:i(ib, May. 15 41-42; July!\n5.4f*b\nOFFICE FURNITURE\nWE SELL, BUY OR EXCHANGE\nChairs Steel Files\nDesks Steel Cabinets\nTables Safes\nBAUM\u2019S FURNITURE HOUSE\nIII# P.re *1. N.W. Phene NA. 21*4\nFirst\nTrust\nLoans\nFor Purchasing a Home or\nRE-FINANCING\nEXPIRING TRUSTS\nNO COMMISSION CHARGE\nNO RENEWALS REQUIRED\nTerm* Arraneed an\nEa\u00bby Monthly Payment*\nmimiu *uilo<n\u00ab 4 v.O*a\nASSOCIATION COUNCIL *f O.C\nRATIONAL\nJ^&miccnenl\nBUILDING ASSOCIATION\nj UNDIH. SUDLUVlJiOM it\nu. 3. TtlAS'jfty 1\nj 949 NINTH STRMT.N:**\nLoans\nON IMPROVED D. C. PROPERTY\nImmediote attention on your application for\nbuying, rebuilding or refinancing.\nLoans repayable monthly.\nNo charge for appraisal if loan is not mode\nInterest charged only on unpaid bolance of\nprincipal.\nEquitable Co-operative\nBuilding Association\n9J5 F STREET N.W.\nOrrmiifd IRIfl\nTO PURCHAS